{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem *Haqeeqat-e-Husn* (\"The Reality of Beauty\") from *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Beauty is personified as directly questioning God (*Khuda*) about its lack of immortality: \"Why was I not with endless life endowed?\"[^1]\n\nGod replies that the world is a transient \"hall of sight\" (*bazm-e-numaish*), a mere story emerging from primordial non-existence (*adam*), inherently composed of ceaseless change (*rang-o-boo-e-taghaiyur*). Thus, \"true beauty is a thing that has to fade\" to fulfill its purpose in this evanescent realm.[^2] \n\nIqbal thereby portrays beauty's metaphysical source as divine (arising from God Himself), yet ontologically bound to impermanence and perceptual revelation (*numaish*) within creation's flux—its reality (*haqeeqat*) inseparable from mortality.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 12 (\"Haqeeqat-e-Husn\"), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/12-haqeeqat-e-husn/translation/#p-dfb149).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 12 (\"Haqeeqat-e-Husn\"), [passage](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/12-haqeeqat-e-husn/translation/#p-dfb149).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 12 (\"Haqeeqat-e-Husn\"), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/12-haqeeqat-e-husn/translation/#p-4a6546).",
